blic schools received an average of about $8,000 per student in the 2011 school year and that is one of the lowest amounts in the nation. One of the best private schools in the state of Colorado (Faith Christian Academy) only charges an average tuition of $5,800 per year. Far from being &quot;bad people&quot; parents who choose private education for their children are not only giving them a gift that will last a lifetime, they are also supporting a system that has proved it is far superior to the public education model. Its time we as citizens stopped griping over traditional party line issues and approached the countries problems from a common sense standpoint. If we look at the facts we can see that private school offers kids a better education at a better price. Instead of throwing more money at the failing public school system we need to ask ourselves why private schools are doing better and how the state governments can help more students benifit from the great private schools already available. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1313" language="en" documentId="2936" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="cOmONsENseANYone" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:00PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="10" thumbsDown="0" origId="2936" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1313"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>